# Development

## Communication Style

In all interactions and commit messages, be extremely concise and sacrifice grammar for the sake of concision. Avoid flattery.

## Development Style

- Follow DRY principles.
- Use PrimeVue components whenever possible
  - Component docs (Markdown): `https://primevue.org/{component}.md`
  - LLM index: `https://primevue.org/llms/` (llms.txt, llms-full.txt)
- Use Tailwind v3 utility classes.
- Enterprise best practices. Interfaces in `types/`, derived from constants when appropriate. Reused patterns in composables, not components.

## TODO / FIXME / HACK Comments

- NEVER remove a `TODO`, `FIXME`, or `HACK` comment. These mark known issues the developer has not yet resolved.
- If a task appears to address the concern a TODO describes, ask the developer before removing it.
- When moving code to a new file or composable, carry all TODO/FIXME/HACK comments with it verbatim.

## No Speculative or "Convenience" Code

- Do NOT add code that is not immediately used. Every line must be called or referenced.
- Do NOT add re-exports or abstractions "for convenience" unless explicitly requested.
- Consult with user before adding helper functions, utility wrappers.
- Do NOT anticipate future needs. Write only what is required for the current task.
- Follow existing project patterns exactly. Do not introduce new patterns or conventions without consultation.

If you write code, something must call it. If nothing calls it, don't write it.

## General Documentation Standards

- Write clear, concise documentation that explains both what and why.
- MCP server config: `.cursor/mcp.json` (project-level; optional `~/.cursor/mcp.json` for global).
- Use markdown format for all documentation files.
- Include code examples where applicable.
- Keep documentation up-to-date with code changes.

## Build & Validation

After every code change, validate the build succeeds: run `npm run build` (or the project build script) before considering the task complete.
